<p><b>Howard C. Nusbaum</b> is professor at the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Chicago" title="University of Chicago">University of Chicago</a>, <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a> in the Department of Psychology and its College, and a steering committee member of the Neuroscience Institute. Nusbaum is an internationally recognized expert in <a href="/wiki/Cognitive_psychology" title="Cognitive psychology">cognitive psychology</a>, <a href="/wiki/Speech_science" title="Speech science">speech science</a>, and in the new field of <a href="/wiki/Social_neuroscience" title="Social neuroscience">social neuroscience</a>. Nusbaum investigates the cognitive and neural mechanisms that mediate <a href="/wiki/Spoken_language" title="Spoken language">spoken language</a> use, as well as <a href="/wiki/Language" title="Language">language</a> learning and the role of <a href="/wiki/Attention" title="Attention">attention</a> in speech perception. In addition, he investigates how we understand the meaning of <a href="/wiki/Music" title="Music">music</a>, and how cognitive and social-emotional processes interact in <a href="/wiki/Decision-making" title="Decision-making">decision-making</a>.</p>
<p></p>
